pan><hr size=1> WRT a sealed cabin...additional space needed would eliminate at least two, maybe 3 rows of first or business class seating.  You need to add a bathroom, a small galley, and a fair amount of storage space.  On oversee flights, you would have to add a significant amount of space because there would be a need for a relief crew, and that means cots.<br>
<br>
Furthermore, if there is a problem in back that is mechanical in nature that needs to be looked at, someone has to check it out.  Flight attendants are not the final authority as to the safety of a flight: the pilot in command is.  Therefore, a problem in back requires someone with the ability to determine safety of flight to analyze the situation, and right now thats the flight deck crew.<br>
<br>
A more secure cockpit is definitely a good thing, but sealed off seems a bit impractical to me.  Perhaps some type of checkpoint system, or a door that can only be opened from INSIDE the cockpit is better than what we have today.  Heck, maybe some type of keyless entry system only the pilots have for boarding?<br>
<br>
WRT lowering cabin pressure, you do run the risk of killing someone by hypoxia (lack of oxygen).  This doesn't affect the pilots (quick donning oxygen masks are standard in all commercial airliners).  However, to detain terrorists, even unconscious ones, someone has to go back and cuff em up.  That acts in contradiction to the sealed cabin theory, unless you have someone in back that can do the deal.<br>
<br>
I don't know the science of a small buddy tank with a regulator, but how small and how concealed can you make one?  They make small ones for military pilots, but could you camoflage one to look like a can of shaving cream?  If so (my thinking is yes), this will give a terrorist a small amount of time to operate in an environment with no one else awake (all out due to the low oxygen solution earlier), and that may be less safe than before.<br>
<br>
That brings us to sky marshals.  The idea of firearms on a pressurized aircraft is generally bad: one stray shot will puncture the hull and you have rapid depressurization.  This WILL damage the aircraft.  One person mentioned special bullets that fragment on hard objects: how hard?  Airplanes are in fact fairly soft (inside and outside) to save weight.  What about the newer types of Non-Lethal Weapons being tested?  These seem to have some promise in street situations, and for the most part it avoids the &quot;bullets in an airplane&quot; problem.<br>
<br>
Armed pilots, or at the very least pilots that are instructed how to defend themselves is something else I would prefer.  Most pilots being ex-military doesn't matter.  Airlines prefer military pilots because they have jet time, high time, and their training requires discipline.  They are not hiring them from the military because they know how to perform basic hand to hand combat moves.  Furthermore, a 20 year airline veteran who hasn't done basic hand to hand since boot is not going to be a match for an in shape, well versed terrorist.  Constant practice will give them a much better chance than training from a point in the past.<br>
<br>
The ultimate answer here is provided by Aolen - &quot;keep the crazies off the plane in the first place&quot;.  That means highly increased security at airports, longer delays boarding, and ultimately a loss of personal freedom this country has been founded on.  Granted, by having intent to do bad things, you give up your rights, but everyone else has to play by the same rules, and everyone will be affected.<br>
<br>
Is this something you are willing to live with?  In my case it is.  However, I have seen several people in airports that don't put up with this now, and won't put up with it in the future.  These are the people that have 3 or 4 carryon's per person, most too big to fit in bins and under seats.  These are the people that show up 3 minutes before departure and demand to have a seat.  These are the people that complain if their omelet is not cooked properly by abusing the flight attendants.  Lastly, these are the people that have a few too many and disrupt the flight in some way because of intoxication.<br>
<br>
Frankly, if the airlines had been bastards about this for the past several years the public would have changed.  Instead, they haven't been because a passenger is a paying customer, and any perception of unfair treatment by that person means loss of business to the airline.  I saw one airline physically enforce the bag limit rule in the last 20 years - ATA - and I was thrilled they did it.<br>
<br>
The ultimate solution will require time, money, and loss of freedom in travel situations.  It will require airports, airlines, and airplane designers working together for the best interest of the public instead of their bottom line.  It will also require the public to accept the change.  This is something I am willing to live with.  Are my neighbors?  Are my friends? <p>Tanuden <BR>
